In the present passage the farmer and the trader typify the contrast between safe but grinding toil for a bare living and the pursuit of a possible fortune at the imminent rislr of losing all. In this way a single statement tells us not only that all men are greedy of gain (cp. note on lucra petens below) but also that they are willing to endure anything to secure it. Thus the reader by the time he reaches the case of Marathus is disposed to be as lenient as possible.
